================================================================================
§1  PURPOSE, SCOPE, AND BACKGROUND
================================================================================

1.1  Purpose
This Occupational Health and Safety Compliance Policy Manual establishes the
mandatory behavioral standards governing all activities conducted within the
production facilities of Kafaoglu Metal Plastik Makine San. ve Tic. A.S.

The Manual defines which observable behaviors on the production floor are
classified as safe or unsafe, and describes the monitoring and alert mechanisms
in place to detect and respond to unsafe behaviors in real time.

1.2  Scope of Application
This Manual applies to all personnel operating on the production floor,
including full-time and temporary employees, subcontractors, maintenance
personnel, and visitors. It defines four specific behavioral domains:
  - Pedestrian movement
  - Equipment intervention
  - Electrical panel management
  - Forklift load management

1.3  Monitoring and Enforcement
The Company has installed an automated real-time behavior detection and warning
system on the production floor. This system continuously monitors live video
feeds from IP cameras installed throughout the facility.

================================================================================
§2  DEFINITIONS AND CLASSIFICATION OF BEHAVIORS
================================================================================

2.1  Behavioral Classification Framework
All observable behaviors on the production floor are classified into two
categories: Safe Behaviors and Unsafe Behaviors. For each of the four
operational domains, a specific safe behavior and a specific unsafe behavior
have been defined.

2.2  Glossary of Terms

  Safe Behavior:
    An observable action that conforms to the operational standards defined in
    this Manual. Safe behaviors do not trigger monitoring alerts.

  Unsafe Behavior:
    An observable action that deviates from the operational standards and
    creates a risk of injury or operational harm. Unsafe behaviors trigger
    the automated alert and reporting system.

  Designated Safe Walkway:
    The pedestrian pathway delineated by GREEN painted floor markings.
    Personnel on foot must remain within these green-marked boundaries.

  Safe Walkway Violation:
    Movement outside the boundaries of the Designated Safe Walkway.

  Green Safety Vest (Authorized):
    The specific GREEN-colored safety vest indicating a personnel member is
    authorized to perform equipment intervention activities.

  Red-Black Safety Vest (General):
    A safety vest of RED and BLACK coloring, worn by general production
    personnel NOT cleared for direct equipment intervention.

  Authorized Intervention:
    Interacting with equipment while wearing the GREEN safety vest.

  Unauthorized Intervention:
    Interacting with equipment while NOT wearing the GREEN safety vest,
    or while not wearing required safety equipment.

  Closed Panel Cover:
    The protective cover of an electrical panel is fully CLOSED.

  Opened Panel Cover:
    The protective cover of an electrical panel is in the OPEN position.

  Safe Carrying:
    Operating a forklift while carrying TWO (2) or fewer standardized blocks.

  Carrying Overload with Forklift:
    Operating a forklift while carrying THREE (3) or more standardized blocks.

================================================================================
§3  PEDESTRIAN WALKWAY REGULATIONS
================================================================================

3.1  Hazard Context
The production floor involves the simultaneous presence of operating machinery,
moving forklifts, and on-foot personnel. The Designated Safe Walkway provides a
defined, physically marked route for all foot traffic.

3.2  Walkway Markings
The Designated Safe Walkway is marked using GREEN painted lines on the
production floor. These green markings define the boundary of the permitted
pedestrian zone. The floor also features YELLOW painted lines delineating
workspace zones.

3.3  Behavioral Standards

  3.3.1  Required Behavior — Safe Walkway (Compliant)
  Movement along the production floor that remains WITHIN the boundaries of the
  green-marked Designated Safe Walkway.

  3.3.2  Non-Compliant Behavior — Safe Walkway Violation
  Movement or presence OUTSIDE the boundaries of the green-marked Designated
  Safe Walkway.

                         *** WARNING ***
  The Safe Walkway Violation is the highest-frequency unsafe behavior recorded
  at this facility. Any deviation from the green-marked boundaries places the
  individual in proximity to forklift and machinery hazards and will be treated
  as an unsafe behavior event requiring immediate response.

================================================================================
§4  EQUIPMENT AND MACHINERY INTERVENTION
================================================================================

4.1  Hazard Context
Interaction with production equipment by personnel who are not cleared creates
risk of injury. Authorized personnel are visually distinguished by the safety
vest they wear.

4.2  Vest Identification System
  - GREEN safety vest: worn by AUTHORIZED personnel cleared for intervention
  - RED-BLACK safety vest: worn by GENERAL personnel NOT cleared for
    equipment intervention

The color of the safety vest is the primary observable criterion for classifying
the behavior as Authorized or Unauthorized Intervention.

4.3  Behavioral Standards

  4.3.1  Required Behavior — Authorized Intervention (Compliant)
  Interaction with production equipment performed by a person wearing the
  designated GREEN safety vest and required safety equipment.

  4.3.2  Non-Compliant Behavior — Unauthorized Intervention
  Any person interacting with equipment who is NOT wearing the GREEN vest must
  be assumed to be performing an Unauthorized Intervention.

                    *** CRITICAL SAFETY NOTICE ***
  The green safety vest is the primary and most readily observable indicator of
  authorization status. Any person seen interacting with equipment who is not
  wearing the green vest must be assumed to be performing an Unauthorized
  Intervention. This classification applies regardless of the person's stated
  intent or role.

================================================================================
§5  ELECTRICAL PANEL COVER MANAGEMENT
================================================================================

5.1  Hazard Context
Electrical panels connected to production machinery are present throughout the
facility. Their covers serve as a protective barrier. Leaving panel covers open
is an identified unsafe behavior.

5.2  Behavioral Standards

  5.2.1  Required Behavior — Closed Panel Cover (Compliant)
  The cover of an electrical panel connected to a production machine is
  fully CLOSED. This is the required state during production operations.

  5.2.2  Non-Compliant Condition — Opened Panel Cover (Unsafe)
  The cover of an electrical panel has been left in the OPEN position.
  This includes both deliberate leaving open and inadvertent forgetting
  to close. The condition is unsafe regardless of how long the panel has
  been open or whether personnel are nearby.

                         *** WARNING ***
  Leaving a panel cover open — even when doing so feels like a minor or
  temporary oversight — is classified as an unsafe behavior under this Manual.
  The automated detection system monitors panel cover status continuously.

================================================================================
§6  FORKLIFT LOAD MANAGEMENT
================================================================================

6.1  Hazard Context
Forklifts operate within the production floor to carry materials. Loads
exceeding the defined safe limit create risks of vehicle instability.

6.2  Load Capacity Definition

  Load Configuration          | Blocks | Compliance Status
  ----------------------------|--------|---------------------------
  Safe Carrying               | ≤ 2    | COMPLIANT — Required
  Carrying Overload (Forklift)| ≥ 3    | NON-COMPLIANT — Unsafe

6.3  Behavioral Standards

  6.3.1  Required Behavior — Safe Carrying (Compliant)
  Operating a forklift while carrying TWO (2) or fewer standardized blocks.

  6.3.2  Non-Compliant Behavior — Carrying Overload with Forklift
  Operating a forklift while carrying THREE (3) or more standardized blocks
  during any phase of a load operation.

                    *** CRITICAL SAFETY NOTICE ***
  The block count threshold is unambiguous: two blocks or fewer is safe; three
  blocks or more is an overload. Any observed forklift load of three or more
  blocks will trigger an immediate alert.

================================================================================
§7  SURVEILLANCE, MONITORING, AND ALERT SYSTEM
================================================================================

7.1  Camera Infrastructure
Two IP cameras (UNV IPC2122CR3-PF40-A) providing Full HD (1920x1080) coverage.
Video feeds are transmitted in real time.

7.2  Automated Behavior Detection
The system identifies the following unsafe behaviors in real time:
  - Safe Walkway Violation (Section 3)
  - Unauthorized Intervention (Section 4)
  - Opened Panel Cover (Section 5)
  - Carrying Overload with Forklift (Section 6)

7.3  Monitoring Interface and Reporting
Reports are produced in text format recording event type, zone, and timestamp.

================================================================================
§8  QUICK REFERENCE: BEHAVIOR CLASSIFICATION SUMMARY
================================================================================

  ID | Domain              | Unsafe Behavior              | Observable Indicator
  ---|---------------------|------------------------------|---------------------------
  0  | Pedestrian Movement | Safe Walkway Violation       | Person outside green floor
     |                     |                              | markings
  1  | Equipment           | Unauthorized Intervention    | Person without green vest
     | Interaction         |                              | interacting with equipment
  2  | Electrical Safety   | Opened Panel Cover           | Panel cover in open
     |                     |                              | position
  3  | Forklift Load       | Carrying Overload (Forklift) | 3+ blocks on forklift forks

  IMPORTANT: Each unsafe behavior has a corresponding safe behavior. The system
  monitors for the four unsafe categories. Safe categories are the default —
  no alert is generated when the safe behavior is observed.
